methods of analysis, she develops approaches for interpreting embodied erotic rhetoric and the marginal cultural practices that construct women’s public erotic bodies. She follows these bodies out into the streets—into the protest spaces where sex workers and anti-rape activists challenge discourses about morality and victimhood and struggle to remake their own identities. Throughout, Werner showcases the voices of these performers and in the analyses shares her experiences as an audience member, interviewer, and paying customer. The result is a uniquely personal and erudite study that advances conversations about women’s agency and erotic performance, moving beyond the binary that views the erotic body as either oppressed or empowered.Theoretically sophisticated and delightfully intimate, Stripped is an important contribution to the study of the rhetoric of the body and to rhetorical and performance studies more broadly.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Rhetoric.2bisacsh  aembodied rhetoric.  aexotic dance.  aneo-burlesque.  aperformance.  arhetorical analysis.  asex work.  astripping.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311074521440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978027108834140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271088341423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271088341/original  a978-3-11-074521-4  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK